<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94: ROUND OF 16; SPOTLIGHT; SYMPATHY . . . WELL, NO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAUL HAYWARD, Daily Telegraph of London 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On Ireland's loss to Holland: 
</P>
<P>
 "To write critically of Ireland has become an unpardonable sin, but this time 
a little ink will flow.Their supporters watch in mute despair as a succession 
of errors halted the Irish advance. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Republic will never again endure such a wretched first half. The 
pillaging of Terry Phelan's left flank led to the first Dutch goal. The second 
belonged in the all-time top 20 of embarrassing World Cup moments as a shot 
from Wim Jonk wriggled through Packie Bonner's gloves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070694-0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 057933 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 6, 1994, Wednesday, Southland Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 6; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
98 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94: ROUND OF 16; SPOTLIGHT; NUMBERS GAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 FIFA, soccer's world governing body, reports it is satisfied with security 
arrangements during the World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
 "Owing to the good spirit of fans and their overall attitude, there has been 
no evidence of hooliganism and no significant incidents have occurred so far," 
a statement said. 
</P>
<P>
 There have been 312 arrests among the more than 2.5 million who have attended 
matches. Of those arrested, 161 involved ticket scalping. Twelve have been 
arrested for public drunkenness. 
</P>
<P>
 There also were 833 cases of fans requiring medical treatment, 95% for 
heat-related problems. ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</TEXT>
