<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; HARVEST CRUSADE IS THIS WEEKEND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Using Gospel messages and Christian rock and pop music to entertain and 
convert, Christian evangelist Greg Laurie will present his fifth annual Harvest 
Crusade in the county this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
 Organizers of the nondenominational crusade expect 150,000 people to attend 
the three-day event at Anaheim Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're very excited," said Richard Cathers, an assistant pastor at Calvary 
Chapel in Anaheim, who has attended every Harvest Crusade in the county. "It's 
always a great time." 
</P>
<P>
 The evangelical crusade begins Friday night at 7:30. 
</P>
<P>
 The program, which includes music by country singer Ricky Skaggs and a 
biblical address by Laurie, the pastor of Harvest Christian Fellowship in 
Riverside, will end at 9 p.m. The event is free. 
</P>
<P>
 The program will be repeated Saturday and Sunday, also at 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 At the end of each night's sermon, Laurie, 41, will invite participants onto 
the stage. 
</P>
<P>
 "People can bring their friends to hear the Gospel and some great music," 
Cathers said. "It's good to have the opportunity to see people get saved." 
</P>
<P>
 This year's crusade will include a Kids' Crusade, aimed at children age 5 
through 12. It will be Saturday at 11 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The children's program will star children's character "Psalty, the Singing 
Songbook," a man who sings biblical hymns while dressed as a large, blue book. 
LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
